2593000 1000 1112000 2908000 -77000 1912000 -58000 783000 -29000 P6Y6M P4Y10M P4Y3M P5Y8M P4Y4M P4Y 25000000 11400000 43800000 200000 200000 -454000 -149000 -43000 7151000 8621000 13638000 3780000 200000 700000 600000 4100000 4100000 3900000 2012 2012 2012 2012 2012 2007 2007 2006 2008 2010 84811000 109100000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">15\. LEGAL PROCEEDINGS </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We and certain current and former officers and directors have been named as defendants in complaints filed by investors in the United States District Court for the District of Colorado. The first complaint was filed in November 2007 and several other complaints were filed shortly thereafter. These actions were consolidated and, in September 2008, the district court appointed a lead plaintiff and counsel. An amended consolidated complaint was filed in December 2008. The amended complaint purports to state claims under Section 10(b), 20(a), and 20A of the Exchange Act on behalf of a class of all persons who purchased our common stock between April 2, 2007 and April 14, 2008 (the &#x201C;Class Period&#x201D;). The amended complaint also added our independent auditor as a defendant. The amended complaint alleges that, during the Class Period, the defendants made false and misleading public statements about us and our business and prospects and, as a result, the market price of our common stock was artificially inflated. The amended complaint also claims that certain current and former officers and directors traded in our common stock on the basis of material non-public information. The amended complaint seeks compensatory damages on behalf of the alleged class in an unspecified amount, including interest, and also added attorneys&#x2019; fees and costs of litigation. On February 28, 2011, the District Court granted motions to dismiss filed by the defendants and dismissed all claims. A final judgment was thereafter entered. Plaintiffs subsequently appealed to the United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit.&nbsp;&nbsp;We and those current and former officers and directors named as defendants have entered into a Stipulation of Settlement with the plaintiffs that would, if approved by the United States District Court for the District of Colorado, resolve all claims asserted against us by the plaintiffs on behalf of the putative class, and plaintiffs&#x2019; appeal would be dismissed. Our independent auditor is not a party to the Stipulation of Settlement. The Stipulation of Settlement is subject to customary conditions, including preliminary court approval, and final court approval following notice to stockholders. If the settlement becomes final, all amounts required by the settlement will be paid by our insurers. There can be no assurance that the settlement will be finally approved by the District Court, or that approval by the District Court will, if challenged, be upheld by the Tenth Circuit.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On October 27, 2010, Spectrum Agencies (&#x201C;Spectrum&#x201D;) filed suit against our subsidiary, Crocs Europe B.V. (&#x201C;Crocs Europe&#x201D;), in the High Court of Justice, Queen&#x2019;s Bench Division, Royal Courts of Justice in London, United Kingdom (&#x201C;UK&#x201D;). Spectrum acted as an agent for Crocs products in the UK from 2005 until Crocs Europe terminated the relationship on July 3, 2008 due to Spectrum&#x2019;s breach of its duty to act in good faith towards Crocs Europe. Spectrum alleges that Crocs Europe unlawfully terminated the agency relationship and failed to pay certain sales commissions. A trial on the liability, not quantum (compensation and damages), was held at the High Court in London from November 30, 2011 to December 5, 2011. On December 16, 2011, the High Court of Justice issued a judgment that found that although Spectrum&#x2019;s actions were a breach of its duty to act in good faith towards Crocs Europe the breach was not sufficiently severe to justify termination. We believe that the trial judge erred in his findings and subsequently appealed the judgment.&nbsp;&nbsp;On October 30, 2012, the Court of Appeal handed down its judgment confirming the trial judge&#x2019;s findings. We submitted a request to the Supreme Court seeking permission to appeal and anticipate that a decision by the Supreme Court on permission to appeal will be rendered in the first quarter of 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;Given that this phase of the proceedings only pertains to liability, there have been no findings in relation to the amount of compensation or damages other than with respect to legal fees. Under English law, the prevailing party is entitled to reimbursement of reasonable legal fees incurred in the liability proceedings. Spectrum has not quantified its claim for compensation and damages and the amount will be assessed later in the proceedings. Proceedings on quantum may be stayed until a decision on permission to appeal has been handed down or in the event that permission is granted, until a final decision on the merits.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We are currently subject to an audit by U.S. Customs &amp; Border Protection (&#x201C;CBP&#x201D;) in respect of the period from 2006 to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">2010</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. CBP issued a draft audit report to which Crocs filed comments and objections.&nbsp; The Company believes that a final report (and notice of a formal claim) will not be issued until sometime in mid-2013.&nbsp; CBP has provided the Company with preliminary projections </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">and a draft audit report </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">that reflect unpaid duties totaling approximat</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ely $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">14.3</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> mi</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">llion during the period under review. The Company has responded that these projections are erroneous and provided arguments that demonstrate the amount due in connection with this matter</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">is considerably less than the preliminary projection.&nbsp; CBP is currently reviewing this response.&nbsp; It is not possible at this time to predict whether the Company&#x2019;s arguments will be successful in eliminating or reducing the amount in dispute. Likewise, it is not possible to predict whether CBP may seek to assert a claim for penalties in addition to any loss of revenue claim.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We are currently subject to an audit by Mexico&#x2019;s Federal Tax Authority (&#x201C;SAT&#x201D;) for the period from </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">January 2006</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to July 2011.&nbsp;&nbsp;There are two phases to the audit, the first for capital equipment and finished goods and the second for raw materials.&nbsp;&nbsp;The first phase is complete and no major discrepancies were noted by the SAT.&nbsp;&nbsp;On January 9, 2013, Crocs received a notice for the second phase in which the SAT proposed a </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">tax assessment (taxes and penalties) </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">of rough</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ly 280 million pesos (approximately $22</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million) ba</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">sed on the value of all of Crocs&#x2019; imported raw materials during the audit period.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that the proposed penalty amount is unfounded and without merit. We have retained local counsel to handle the matter and who will argue that the amount due in connection with the matter, if any, is substantially less than that proposed by the SAT.&nbsp;&nbsp;We expect it to take between two and three years for resolution of this matter in the Mexican courts.&nbsp;&nbsp;It is not possible at this time to predict the outcome of this matter or reasonably estimate any potential loss.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">December 31, 2012, w</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">e have accrued a total of $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">5.9</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million related to these legal matters.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Although we are subject to other litigation from time to time in the ordinary course of business, including employment, intellectual property and product liability claims, we are not party to any other pending legal proceedings that we believe will have a material adverse impact on our business.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 3067000 </table></div> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Long-term </font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Debt A</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">greement</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On December 10, 2012, Crocs, Inc. (&#x201C;</font><font style="display: inline;">the Company&#x201D;) entered into a Master Installment Payment Agreement (&#x201C;</font><font style="display: inline;">Master </font><font style="display: inline;">IPA&#x201D;) with PNC Bank National Association (&#x201C;PNC&#x201D;) in which PNC will finance the Company</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2019;s purchase of</font><font style="display: inline;"> software and services, which may include but are not limited to third party costs to design, install and implement software systems, and associated hardware described in the schedules defined within the Master IPA. This agreement was </font><font style="display: inline;">entered into</font><font style="display: inline;"> to finance the recent implementation of </font><font style="display: inline;">a new enterprise resource planning (&#x201C;ERP&#x201D;) system</font><font style="display: inline;"> which began in October 2012 and is estimated to continue through early 2014. The terms of the agreement consist of variable interest rates and payment terms based on amounts borrowed and timing of activity throughout the implementation of </font><font style="display: inline;">the ERP</font><font style="display: inline;">. As of </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2</font><font style="display: inline;">012, </font><font style="display: inline;">we had $</font><font style="display: inline;">6.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million of long-term debt outstanding</font><font style="display: inline;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">of which $2.0 million represent current installments,</font><font style="display: inline;"> under the agreement payable over the next four years bearing interest at rate of </font><font style="display: inline;">2.63</font><font style="display: inline;">%. Interest ra</font><font style="display: inline;">tes and payment terms are subject to changes as further financing occurs under the Master IPA.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Revolving Credit Facility</font> </p> <p style="margin:4.5pt 0pt 0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On December&nbsp;10, 2012, Crocs,&nbsp;Inc. (the &#x201C;Company&#x201D;) and its subsidiaries, Crocs Retail,&nbsp;Inc., Ocean Minded,&nbsp;Inc., Jibbitz, LLC and Bite,&nbsp;Inc. (collectively with the Company, the &#x201C;Borrowers&#x201D;) entered into the First Amendment to Amended and Restated Credit Agreement (the &#x201C;First Amendment&#x201D;) with the lenders named therein and PNC Bank, National Association (&#x201C;PNC&#x201D;), as a lender and administrative agent for the lenders, pursuant to which certain terms of the Amended and Restated Credit Agreement (the &#x201C;Credit Agreement&#x201D;), dated December&nbsp;16, 2011, were amended. The First Amendment, among other things, (i)&nbsp;extends the maturity date from December&nbsp;16, 2016 to December&nbsp;16, 2017, (ii)&nbsp;increases the total commitments under the revolving credit facility from $70 million to $100 million, with the ability to increase commitments to up to $125 million subject to certain conditions, (iii)&nbsp;decreases the revolving interest rate by 50 basis points for both domestic and LIBOR rate loans, (iv)&nbsp;increases the ability of the Company to make stock repurchases from up to $25 million per year to up to $150 million per year, subject to certain conditions, (v)&nbsp;increases the limit for permitted acquisitions from up to $40 million per year to up to $100 million per year, subject to certain conditions, (vi)&nbsp;adds a covenant to maintain unrestricted cash of at least $100 million at all times, subject to limitations, and (vii)&nbsp;amends certain restrictive covenants to be more favorable to the Borrowers. </font> </p> <p style="margin:4.5pt 0pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The Credit Agreement is available for working capital, capital expenditures, permitted acquisitions, reimbursement of drawings under letters of credit, and permitted dividends, distributions, purchases, redemptions and retirements of equity interests. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement are secured by all of our assets including all receivables, equipment, general intangibles, inventory, investment property, subsidiary stock and intellectual property. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement bear interest at a variable rate. For domestic rate loans, the interest rate is equal to the highest of (i)&nbsp;the daily federal funds open rate as quoted by ICAP North America, Inc. plus 0.5%, (ii)&nbsp;PNC&#x2019;s prime rate and (iii)&nbsp;a daily LIBOR rate plus 1.0%, in each case there is an additional margin ranging from 0.25% to 1.00% based on certain conditions. For LIBOR rate loans, the interest rate is equal to a LIBOR rate plus a margin ranging from 1.25% to 2.00% based on certain conditions. The Credit Agreement requires monthly interest payments with respect to domestic rate loans and at the end of each interest period with respect to LIBOR rate loans and contains certain customary restrictive and financial covenants. We were in compliance with these restrictive financial covenants as of December 31, 2012.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of December 31, 2012 and 2011, we had no outstanding borrowings and $0.4 million of outstanding borrowings, respectively, under the Credit Agreement. As of </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2012 and 2011</font><font style="display: inline;">, we had issued and outstanding letters of credit of $</font><font style="display: inline;">6.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and $</font><font style="display: inline;">6.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively, which were reserved against the borrowing base under the terms of our revolving credit facility. During the years ended </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2012 and 2011</font><font style="display: inline;">, we capitalized $</font><font style="display: inline;">0.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and $</font><font style="display: inline;">0.4</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively, in fees and third party costs which were incurred in connection with the Credit Agreement, as deferred financing costs.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Maturities of Debt and Capital Lease Obligations</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: Accounting Pronouncements</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In December 2011, the FASB issued ASU No. 2011-11, &#x201C;Disclosures about Offsetting Assets and Liabilities.&#x201D; This pronouncement was issued to enhance disclosure requirements surrounding the nature of an entity&#x2019;s right to offset and related arrangements associated with its financial instruments and derivative instruments. This new guidance requires companies to disclose both gross and net information about instruments and transactions eligible for offset in the statement of financial position and instruments and transactions subject to master netting arrangements. This pronouncement is effective for reporting periods beginning on or after January 1, 2013. We do not anticipate the adoption of ASU 2011-11 to have a material impact to the consolidated financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In January 20</font><font style="display: inline;">13, the FASB issued ASU No. 2013-01, &#x201C;Clarifying the Scope of Disclosures about Offsetting Assets and Liabilities</font><font style="display: inline;">.&#x201D; This pronoun</font><font style="display: inline;">cement was issued to address implementation issues about the scope of Accounting Standards Update No. 2011-11 and to clarify the scope of the offsetting disclosures and address any unintended consequences.</font><font style="display: inline;"> This pronouncement is effective for reporting periods beginning on or after January 1, 2013. 31, 2012 and 2011</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:9pt;">, respectively, as amounts are related to our subsidiaries in China</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:9pt;">.</font></font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Asset Retirement Obligations</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We record a liability equal to the fair value of the estimated future cost to retire an asset, if the liability&#x2019;s fair value can be reasonably estimated. Our asset retirement obligation (&#x201C;ARO&#x201D;) liabilities are primarily associated with the disposal of property and equipment which we are contractually obligated to remove at the end of certain retail and office leases in order to restore the facilities back original condition as specified in the related lease agreements. We estimate the fair value of these liabilities based on current store closing costs and discount the costs back as if they were to be performed at the inception of the lease. At the inception of such leases, we record the ARO as a liability and also record a related asset in an amount equal to the estimated fair value of the obligation. The capitalized asset is then depreciated on a straight-line basis over the useful life of the asset. Upon retirement of the ARO liability, any difference between the actual retirement costs incurred and the previously recorded estimated ARO liability is recognized as a gain or loss in the consolidated statements of operations.</font><font style="display: inline;"> Our</font><font style="display: inline;"> ARO liability as of </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2012 </font><font style="display: inline;">and 2011</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">was $</font><font style="display: inline;">2.4</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million</font><font style="display: inline;"> and $</font><font style="display: inline;">1.9</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 66517000 63976000 84760000 92278000 8273000 8147000 41665000 36343000 76506000 81371000 8429000 13588000 5476000 10226000 89757000 104718000 14821000 19688000 293959000 307823000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Defined contribution plans</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;</font><font style="display: inline;">We have a 401(k) plan known as the Crocs, Inc. 401(k) Plan (the &#x201C;Plan&#x201D;). The Plan is available to employees on our U.S. payroll and provides employees with tax deferred salary deductions and alternative investment options. The Plan does not provide employees with the option to invest in our common stock. Employees may contribute up to 75.0% of their salary, subject to certain limitations. We match employees&#x2019; contributions to the Plan up to a maximum of </font><font style="display: inline;">4.0</font><font style="display: inline;">% of eligible compensation. The agreement also provides that we meet minimum purchase requirements to maintain exclusivity throughout the term of the agreement, which expires December&nbsp;31, 2014. Historically, the minimum purchase requirements have not been onerous and we do not expect them to become onerous in the future. Depending on the material purchased, pricing is either based on contracted price or is subject to quarterly reviews and fluctuates based on order volume, currency fluctuations and raw material prices. Pursuant to the agreement, we guarantee the payment for certain third party manufacturer purchases of these raw materials up to a maximum potential amount </font><font style="display: inline;">of &#x20AC;</font><font style="display: inline;">3.5</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million (approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;">4.6</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million a</font><font style="display: inline;">s of </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2012</font><font style="display: inline;">), through a letter of credit that was issued to Finproject&nbsp;S.r.l.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 0.001 0.001 250000000 250000000 90306432 91047297 89807146 88662845 90000 91000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Basis of Consolidation and Variable Interest Entities</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of our wholly-owned and majority-owned subsidiaries as well as variable interest entities (&#x201C;VIE&#x201D;) for which we are the primary beneficiary after the elimination of intercompany accounts and transactions. The primary beneficiary of a VIE is the entity that has (i) the power to direct the activities of the VIE that most significantly impact the VIE&#x2019;s economic performance and (ii) the obligation to absorb losses of the VIE that could potentially be significant to the VIE or the right to receive benefits from the VIE that could potentially be significant to the VIE.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 7902000 8766000 364631000 464493000 515324000 2300000 2900000 4300000 14700000 11500000 4600000 47000 4798000 -6364000 17923000 19758000 22953000 18065000 24721000 17186000 95000 165000 597000 1143000 6635000 0.0263 -2338000 -3981000 400000 500000 -4999000 1519000 5016000 -4999000 -819000 -2981000 -4016000 7047000 6284000 30375000 34112000 8641000 8994000 3177000 5392000 7630000 8865000 12575000 12934000 5644000 921000 25900000 6054000 3492000 33889000 22406000 2889000 2405000 -1009000 -779000 -4746000 -7596000 3300000 4600000 5800000 0.040 0.040 0.040 29500000 27500000 23100000 37059000 8935000 6772000 2018000 17725000 13351000 5983000 37263000 9203000 6084000 2584000 17871000 11657000 7735000 36694000 9849000 6922000 3116000 19887000 7003000 9804000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">7\. DERIVATIVE FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We transact business in various foreign countries and are therefore exposed to foreign currency exchange rate risk inherent in revenues, costs, and monetary assets and liabilities denominated in non-functional currencies. We </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">have </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">enter</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ed</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> into foreign currency exchange forward contract</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and currency swap derivative instruments </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">to selectively protect against volatility in the value of non-functional currency denominated monetary assets and liabilities, and of future cash flows caused by changes in foreig</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">n currency exchange rates. We do not designate these</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">derivative instruments</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> as hedging instruments under the accounting standards for derivatives and hedging.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> Accordingly, these instruments are recorded at fair value as a derivative asset or liability on the balance sheet with their corresponding change in fair value recognized in Foreign currency transaction (gains) losses, net, in our consolidated statements of operations. For purposes of the cash flow statement, t</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">he Company classifies the cash flows at settlement from undesignated instruments in the same category as the cash flows from the related hedged </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">items, generally within Cash provided by operating activities</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The following table summarizes the notional amounts of the outstanding foreign cur</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">rency exchange contracts at </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">December 31, 2012 and 2011</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. The notional amounts of the derivative financial instruments shown below are denominated in their U.S. dollar equivalents and represent the amount of all contracts of the foreign currency specified. These notional values do not necessarily represent amounts exchanged by the parties and, therefore, are not a direct measure of our exposure to the foreign currency exchange risks.</font> </p> <p style="display: inline;">Foreign currency transaction (gains) losses, net</font></p> </td> </tr> </table></div> <p style="margin:4.5pt 0pt 0pt; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;background-color:yellow;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Derivative Foreign Currency Contracts</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;We are directly and indirectly affected by fluctuations in foreign currency rates which may adversely impact our financial performance. To mitigate the potential impact of foreign currency exchange rate risk, we may employ derivative financial instruments including forward contracts and option contracts. Forward contracts are agreements to buy or sell a quantity of a currency at a predetermined future date and at a predetermined rate. An option contract is an agreement that conveys the purchaser the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell a quantity of a currency at a predetermined rate during a period or at a time in the future. These derivative financial instruments are viewed as risk management tools and are not used for trading or speculative purposes. We recognize derivative financial instruments as either assets or liabilities in the consolidated balance sheets and measure those instruments at fair value. Changes in the fair value of derivatives not designated or effective as hedges are recorded in </font><font style="display: inline;">&#x201C;foreign currency transaction (gains)/losses, net&#x201D; in the c</font><font style="display: inline;">onsolidated statements of operations. We had no derivative instruments that qualified for hedge accounting during any of the periods presented. See Note&nbsp;7&#x2014;Fair Value Measurements and Financial Instruments for further discussion.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 0.78 0.24 1.27 0.62 0.34 0.06 0.32 1.46 0.68 0.50 -0.04 0.76 0.24 1.24 0.61 0.33 0.06 0.31 1.44 0.68 0.49 -0.04 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Earnings per Share</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Basic and diluted earnings (loss) per common share (&#x201C;EPS&#x201D;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings (loss) attributable to common stockholders by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is an unvested share-based payment award containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends and must be included in the computation of earnings per share pursuant to the two-class method. Shares of the Company&#x2019;s non-vested restricted stock awards are considered participating securities. Diluted EPS reflects the potential dilution from securities that could share in the earnings of the Company. Anti-dilutive securities are excluded from diluted EPS. See Note&nbsp;12&#x2014;Earnings per Share for further discussion.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">12\. Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Non-Recurring Fair Value Measurements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The majority of our non-financial instruments, which include inventories, property and equipment and intangible assets, are not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. However, if certain triggering events occur such that a non-financial instrument is required to be evaluated for impairment and the carrying value is not recoverable, the carrying value would be adjusted to the lower of its cost or fair value and an impairment charge would be recorded. See Note 3 &#x2013; Property and Equipment and Note 4 &#x2013; Goodwill &amp; Intangible Assets for discussions on impairment charges recorded during the periods presented.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Management Estimates</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;The preparation of financial statements in conformity with generally accepted accounting principles in the United States of America (&#x201C;GAAP&#x201D;) requires management to make estimates, judgments and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period. Management believes that the estimates, judgments and assumptions made when accounting for items and matters such as, but not limited to, the allowance for doubtful accounts, sales returns, impairment assessments and charges, recoverability of assets (including deferred tax assets), uncertain tax positions, share-based compensation expense, the assessment of lower of cost or market on inventory, useful lives assigned to long-lived assets, depreciation and provisions for contingencies are reasonable based on information available at the time they are made. Management also makes estimates in the assessments of potential losses in relation to tax </font><font style="display: inline;">and customs </font><font style="display: inline;">matters and threatened or pending legal proceedings (see Note&nbsp;15&#x2014;Legal Proceedings). Actual results could materially differ from these estimates. For matters not related to income taxes, if a loss is considered probable and the amount can be reasonably estimated, we recognize an expense for the estimated loss. If there is the potential to recover a portion of the estimated loss from a third party, we make a separate assessment of recoverability and reduce the estimated loss if recovery is deemed probable.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Fair Value</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Fair value is the price that would be received from the sale of an asset or transfer of a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. When determining the fair value measurements for assets and liabilities which are required to be recorded at fair value, we consider the principal or most advantageous market in which a hypothetical sale or transfer would take place and consider assumptions that market participants would use when pricing the asset or liability, such as inherent risk, transfer restrictions, and risk of non-performance.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The fair value hierarchy is made up of three levels of inputs which may be used to measure fair value: </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Level&nbsp;1&#x2014;observable inputs such as quoted prices for identical instruments in active markets; </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Level&nbsp;2&#x2014;observable inputs such as quoted prices for similar instruments in active markets, quoted prices for identical or similar instruments in markets that are not active and model derived valuations in which all significant inputs are observable in active markets; and </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Level&nbsp;3&#x2014;unobservable inputs for which there is little or no market data and which require us to develop our own assumptions. We categorize fair value measurements within the fair value hierarchy based upon the lowest level of the most significant inputs used to </font><font style="display: inline;">determine such fair value measurement.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Cash equivalents primarily include time deposits and certificates of deposit with original maturities of three months or less. Time deposits and certificates of deposit included in cash equivalents are valued at amortized cost, which approximates fair value. These investments have been classified as a Level 1 measurement.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Derivative financial instruments are required to be recorded at their fair value, on a recurring basis. The fair values of our derivative instruments are determined using a discounted cash flow valuation model. The significant inputs used in the model are readily available in public markets or can be derived from observable market transactions, and therefore, have been classified as Level&nbsp;2. These inputs include the applicable exchange rates and forward rates, and discount rates based on the prevailing LIBOR deposit rates.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Our other financial instruments are not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. The carrying value of these financial instruments, including cash equivalents, accounts receivable, accounts payable and accrued liabilities, approximates fair value due to their short maturities. Based on borrowing rates currently available to us, with similar terms, the carrying values of capital lease obligations and the line of credit approximate their fair values.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Inventories and long-lived assets such as property and equipment and intangible assets are also not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. For a discussion of inventory estimated fair value see &#x201C;Inventory Valuation&#x201D; below. However, when determining impairment losses, the fair values of property and equipment and intangibles must be determined. For such determination, we </font><font style="display: inline;">geneally </font><font style="display: inline;">use either an income approach with inputs that are mainly unobservable, such as expected future cash flows, or a market approach using observable inputs such as replacement cost or third party appraisals, as appropriate. Estimated future cash flows are based on management&#x2019;s operating budgets and forecasts which take into consideration both observable and unobservable inputs including growth rates, pricing, new markets and other factors expected to affect the business, as well as management&#x2019;s forecasts for inventory, receivables, capital spending, and other cash needs.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">See Note&nbsp;6</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;</font><font style="display: inline;">Fair Value Measurements</font><font style="display: inline;"> for further discussion related to </font><font style="display: inline;">fair value measurements.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 36170000 4743000 2994000 22156000 5641000 636000 49169000 4856000 3522000 33933000 6222000 636000 4771000 14956000 5689000 8531000 10003000 13139000 84700000 4743000 6109000 66530000 6321000 997000 106258000 4856000 6161000 87426000 7145000 670000 48530000 3115000 44374000 680000 361000 57089000 2639000 53493000 923000 34000 596000 596000 5548000 5548000 1035000 1035000 295000 295000 2325000 4886000 -2500000 -1334000 11892000 -13928000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Foreign Currency Translation and Foreign Currency Transactions</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Our </font><font style="display: inline;">reporting</font><font style="display: inline;"> currency is the U.S. dollar. Assets and liabilities of foreign operations denominated in local currencies are translated at the rate of exchange at the balance sheet date. Revenues and expenses are translated at the weighted average rate of exchange during the applicable period. Adjustments resulting from translating foreign functional currency financial statements into U.S. dollars are included in the foreign currency translation adjustment, a component of accumulated other comprehensive income in stockholders&#x2019; equity. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Gains and losses generated by transactions denominated in </font><font style="display: inline;">currencies other than the local functional</font><font style="display: inline;"> currencies are reflected in the consolidated statement of operations in the period in which they occur and are primarily associated with payables and receivables arising from intercompany transa</font><font style="display: inline;">ctions.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 16196000 20827000 540000 -7200000 2729000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;background-color:lime;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">4\. GOODWILL &amp; INTANGIBLE ASSETS</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">T</font><font style="display: inline;">he inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Intangible Assets</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#x2014;Intangible assets that are determined to have finite lives are amortized over their useful lives on a straight-line basis. Customer relationships are amortized on a straight-line basis or an accelerated basis. Indefinite lived intangible assets, such as trade names, are not amortized and are evaluated for impairment at least annually and when circumstances imply possible impairment. </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Amortization of manufacturing intangible assets is included in cost of sales on the consolidated statements of operations. Amortization related to corporate, non-product and non-manufacturing assets such as our global information systems is included in selling, general and administrative expenses on the consolidated statements of operations. The following table sets forth our definite lived intangible assets and the periods over which they are amortized.</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" align="center" style="border-collapse:collapse;width: 75.00%;margin-left:0pt;"> <tr> <td valign="bottom" style="width:215.00pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 1pt;border-bottom:1pt solid #000000 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:8pt;">Intangible Asset Class</font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:195.40pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 1pt;border-bottom:1pt solid #000000 ;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:8pt;">Weighted Average Amortization Period</font></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="width:215.00pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10pt;text-indent: -10pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="text-indent:0pt;margin-left:-10pt; width:192.65pt; overflow: hidden; white-space: nowrap;"><font style="display: inline;">Capitalized software</font>...................................................</font><font style="text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt; width:-1pt;text-align:right"><font style="display: inline;"></font></font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:195.40pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Shorter of 7&nbsp;years or useful life</font></p> </td> </tr> </table></div> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 31.5pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Capitalized Software</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;We capitalize certain internal and external software acquisition and development costs, including the costs of employees and contractors devoting time to the software development projects and external direct costs for materials and services. Initial costs associated with internally-developed-and-used software are expensed until it is determined that the project has reached the application development stage. Once in its development stage, subsequent additions, modifications or upgrades to an internal-use software project are capitalized to the extent that they add functionality. Software maintenance and training costs are expensed in the period in which they are incurred. Capitalized software primarily consists of our enterprise resource system software, warehouse management software and point of sale software. At least annually, we consider the potential impairment of capitalized software by assessing the substantive service potential of the software, changes, if any, in the extent or manner in which the software is used or is expected to be used, and the actual cost of software development or modification compared to expected cost. See Note&nbsp;4&#x2014;Goodwill and Intangible Assets for further discussion.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 31.5pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Impairment of Intangible Assets</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Intangible assets with indefinite lives are evaluated for impairment when events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying value may not be fully recoverable and at least annually. Intangible assets that are determined to have definite lives are amortized over their useful lives and are evaluated for impairment only when events or circumstances indicate a carrying value may not be fully recoverable. Recoverability is based on the estimated future undiscounted cash flows of the asset. If the asset is not supported on an undiscounted cash flow basis, the amount of impairment is measured as the difference between its carrying value and its fair value.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Goodwill</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;</font><font style="display: inline;">Goodwill</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> represents the excess purchase price paid over the fair value of assets acquired and liabilities assumed in acquisitions</font><font style="display: inline;">. Goodwill is</font><font style="display: inline;"> considered an indefinite lived asset and therefore is not amortized.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">The Company assesses goodwill for impairment annually on the last day of the fourth quarter, or more frequently if events and circumstances indicate impairment may have occurred. If the carrying value of goodwill exceeds its implied fair value, the Company records an impairment loss equal to the difference. See </font><font style="display: inline;">Note&nbsp;4</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;</font><font style="display: inline;">Goodwill</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> and Intangible Assets for discussion of goodwill balances. There was no impairment of goodwill for the year ended</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 423764000 119206000 536410000 170218000 147175000 99811000 144799000 607977000 196085000 160743000 106350000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Impairment of Long-Lived Assets</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Long-lived assets to be held and used are evaluated for impairment when events or circumstances indicate the carrying value of a long-lived asset may not be fully recoverable. Events that may indicate the impairment of a long-lived asset (or asset group, as defined below) include; (i)&nbsp;a significant decrease in its market price, (ii)&nbsp;a significant adverse change in the extent or manner in which it is being used or in its physical condition, (iii)&nbsp;a significant adverse change in legal factors or business climate that could affect its value, including an adverse action or assessment by a regulator, (iv)&nbsp;an accumulation of costs significantly in excess of the amount originally expected for its acquisition or construction, (v)&nbsp;its current period operating or cash flow losses combined with historical operating or cash flow losses or a forecast of its cash flows demonstrate continuing losses associated with its use, and (vi)&nbsp;a current expectation that, more likely than not, it will be sold or otherwise disposed of significantly before the end of its previously estimated useful life. If such facts indicate a potential impairment of a long-lived asset (or asset group), we assess the recoverability by determining if its carrying value exceeds the sum of its projected undiscounted cash flows from its use and eventual disposition over its remaining economic life. If the asset is not supported on an undiscounted cash flow basis, the amount of impairment is measured as the difference between its carrying value and its fair value. Assets held for sale are reported at the lower of the carrying amount or fair value less costs to sell. Assets to be abandoned or from which no further benefit is expected are written down to zero at the time that the determination is made and the assets are removed entirely from service.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">An asset group is the lowest level of assets and liabilities for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent of the cash flows of other assets and liabilities.&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;">For assets involved in our retail business our asset group is at the retail store level.</font><font style="display: inline;"> See Note 3 &#x2013; Property and Equipment for a discussion of impairment losses recorded during the periods presented.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> -14835000 -12057000 12060000 95627000 148747000 133488000 80792000 136690000 145548000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p><p style="page-break-after:always">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">1</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">1\. </table></div> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We do not provide for deferred taxes on the excess of the financial reporting basis over the tax basis in our investments in foreign subsidiaries that are essentially permanent in duration. In general, it is our practice and intention to reinvest the earnings of our foreign subsidiaries in those operations. Generally, the earnings of our foreign subsidiaries become subject to U.S. taxation upon the remittance of dividends and under certain other circumstances. Exceptions may be made on a year-by-year basis to repatriate current year earnings of certain foreign subsidiaries based on cash needs in the U.S. As of </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2012</font><font style="display: inline;">, we have provided for deferred U.S. income tax </font><font style="display: inline;">of $</font><font style="display: inline;">7.6</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;m</font><font style="display: inline;">illion </font><font style="display: inline;">on $</font><font style="display: inline;">38.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;m</font><font style="display: inline;">illion of foreign subsidiary earnings. No withholding tax is due with respect to the repatriation of these earnings to the U.S. and none has been provided for.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">At </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2012 and 2011</font><font style="display: inline;">, U.S. income and foreign withholding taxes have not been provided </font><font style="display: inline;">on for approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;">490.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and $</font><font style="display: inline;">371.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively, of unremitted earnings of subsidiaries operating outside of the U.S. These earnings are estimated to represent the excess of the financial reporting over the tax basis in our investments in those subsidiaries. These earnings, which are considered to be indefinitely reinvested, would become subject to U.S. income tax if they were remitted to the U.S. The amount of unrecognized deferred U.S. income tax liability on the unremitted earnings has not been determined because the hypothetical calculation is not practicable.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We have deferred tax assets related to certain deductible temporary differences in various tax jurisdictions for which we have recorded a valuation allowance </font><font style="display: inline;">of $</font><font style="display: inline;">25.9</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million</font><font style="display: inline;"> against these deferred tax assets because we do not believe that it is more likely than not that we will be able to realize these deferred tax assets. The significant components of the deferred tax assets for which a valuation allowance has been applied consist of net operating losses in certain tax jurisdictions for which management believes there is not sufficient positive evidence that such net operating losses will be realized against future income and book expenses not deductible for tax purposes in the current year such as inventory impairment reserves, equity compensation and unrealized foreign exchange loss that would increase such net operating losses in the same jurisdictions. These temporary differences are amounts which arose in jurisdictions where (i)&nbsp;current losses exist, (ii)&nbsp;such losses are in excess of any loss carryback potential, (iii)&nbsp;no tax planning strategies exist with which to overcome such losses and (iv)&nbsp;no profits are projected for the following year. For these reasons it is determined that it is more likely than not that these deferred tax assets will not be realized and a valuation allowance has been provided with respect to these deferred tax assets.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">At Decembe</font><font style="display: inline;">r&nbsp;31, 2012, we</font><font style="display: inline;"> had U.S. federal net op</font><font style="display: inline;">erating loss carryforwards of $</font><font style="display: inline;">0.7</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;m</font><font style="display: inline;">illion, state net operating loss carryforwards of $</font><font style="display: inline;">89.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, charitable contribution carryforwards of $</font><font style="display: inline;">23.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and foreign tax credits</font><font style="display: inline;"> of</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;$</font><font style="display: inline;">5.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million</font><font style="display: inline;"> which will expire at various dates b</font><font style="display: inline;">etween 2014 and 2031. We</font><font style="display: inline;"> do not believe that it is more likely than not that the benefit from certain state net operating losses will be realized. Consequently, we have a valuation allowanc</font><font style="display: inline;">e of $</font><font style="display: inline;">9.1</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;mi</font><font style="display: inline;">llion on the deferred tax assets relating to these state net operating loss carryf</font><font style="display: inline;">orwards and charitable contribution carryforwards.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">At Decembe</font><font style="display: inline;">r&nbsp;31, 2012, w</font><font style="display: inline;">e have a foreign deferred tax a</font><font style="display: inline;">sset of $</font><font style="display: inline;">11.4</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million</font><font style="display: inline;"> reflecting the benef</font><font style="display: inline;">it of $</font><font style="display: inline;">43.8</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;milli</font><font style="display: inline;">on in foreign net operating loss carryforwards, some of which have an indefinite life.&nbsp;&nbsp;We do not believe it is more likely than not that the benefit from c</font><font style="display: inline;">ertain foreign net operating loss carryforwards will be realized. Consequently, we have provided a valuation allowance of $</font><font style="display: inline;">7.7</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million on the</font><font style="display: inline;"> deferred tax assets relating to these foreign net operating loss carryforwards.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We had approx</font><font style="display: inline;">imately $</font><font style="display: inline;">36.7</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million in net d</font><font style="display: inline;">eferred tax assets at December&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">31, 2012. A</font><font style="display: inline;">pproxima</font><font style="display: inline;">tely $</font><font style="display: inline;">11.9</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;millio</font><font style="display: inline;">n of the net deferred tax assets were located in foreign jurisdictions for which a sufficient history and expected future profits indicated that it is more likely than not that such deferred tax assets will be realized. Pre-tax profit of appro</font><font style="display: inline;">ximately $</font><font style="display: inline;">47.4</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million is</font><font style="display: inline;"> required to realize the net deferred tax assets.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">At December&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">31, 2012, a</font><font style="display: inline;">ppro</font><font style="display: inline;">ximately $</font><font style="display: inline;">3.8</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million of net deferre</font><font style="display: inline;">d tax assets consists of deferred tax assets related to estimated liabilities for uncertain tax positions that would be realized if such liabilities are actually incurred. The deferred tax assets represent primarily the reduction in tax expense that would occur upon an increase of intercompany royalty expense by various taxing authorities. Approximatel</font><font style="display: inline;">y $</font><font style="display: inline;">15.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million of taxa</font><font style="display: inline;">ble income would have to be recognized to realize these deferred tax assets.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As a result of certain accounting realization requirements, the table of deferred tax assets and liabilities shown above does not include certain deferred tax ass</font><font style="display: inline;">ets at December&nbsp;31, 2012 tha</font><font style="display: inline;">t arose directly from tax deductions related to equity compensation in excess of compensation recognized for financial reporting. Equity will b</font><font style="display: inline;">e increased by $</font><font style="display: inline;">1</font><font style="display: inline;">1.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;"> if and when such deferred tax assets are ultimately realized. We use ASC 740 ordering for purposes of determining when excess tax benefits have been realized.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font 14205000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Income Taxes</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Income taxes are accounted for using the asset and liability method which requires the recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities for the expected future tax consequences of temporary differences between the carrying amounts and the tax basis of other assets and liabilities. We provide for income taxes at the current and future enacted tax rates and laws applicable in each taxing jurisdiction. We use a two-step approach for recognizing and measuring tax benefits taken or expected to be taken in a tax return and disclosures regarding uncertainties in income tax positions. We recognize interest and penalties related to income tax matters in income tax expense in the consolidated statement of operations. See Note&nbsp;11&#x2014;Income Taxes for further discussion.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 12689000 30314000 99000 13165000 23278000 9475000 -228000 1097000 4907000 27908000 13328000 35493000 20344000 19922000 8016000 -2230000 17598000 25490000 -38000 343000 2154000 2113563 1663484 1017311 111000 113000 48641000 59931000 48641000 59931000 657000 853000 837000 639000 843000 619000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">2\. Also during the years ended </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2012, 2011 and 2010</font><font style="display: inline;">, we recognized a gai</font><font style="display: inline;">n of $</font><font style="display: inline;">0.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million,</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;$</font><font style="display: inline;">0.7</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and $</font><font style="display: inline;">0.2</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, re</font><font style="display: inline;">spectively, and a net reduction of inventory of </font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">1.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million,</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;$</font><font style="display: inline;">1.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and $</font><font style="display: inline;">0.6</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, re</font><font style="display: inline;">spectively, as the fair value of the inventory contributed exceeded its carrying amount.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 124203000 155833000 129627000 164804000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Inventory Valuation</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Inventories are valued at the lower of cost or market. Inventory cost is determined using the moving average cost method. At least annually, we evaluate our inventory for possible impairment using standard categories to classify inventory based on the degree to which we believe that the products may need to be discounted below cost to sell within a reasonable period. We base inventory fair value on several subjective assumptions including estimated future demand and market conditions, as well as other observable factors such as current sell-through of our products, recent changes in demand for our products, global and regional economic conditions, historical experience selling through liquidation and price discounted channels and the amount of inventory on hand. If the estimated inventory fair value is less than its carrying value, the carrying value is adjusted to market value and the resulting impairment charge is recorded in cost of sales on the consolidated statements of oper</font><font style="display: inline;">ations. S</font><font style="display: inline;">ee Note&nbsp;2&#x2014;Inventories for further discussi</font><font style="display: inline;">on related to inventorie</font><font style="display: inline;">s.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 5133000 8060000 291000 911000 65338000 88653000 6000000 6400000 203673000 212238000 695453000 829638000 155303000 157938000 422000 5900000 6582000 4596000 2013000 1280000 1666000 1623000 68005000 68713000 5245000 8917000 -16625000 -42078000 -41664000 -65943000 104274000 142376000 128356000 67726000 67726000 21504000 112788000 112788000 55506000 30207000 5571000 28346000 131343000 131343000 61524000 45080000 -3607000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Recently Adopted Accounting </font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Pronouncement</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">s</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In May&nbsp;2011, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#x201C;FASB&#x201D;) issued Accounting Standards Update (&#x201C;ASU&#x201D;) No.&nbsp;2011-04, &#x201C;Amendments to Achieve Common Fair Value Measurement and Disclosure Requirements in U.S. GAAP and International Financial Reporting Standards (&#x201C;IFRS&#x201D;).&#x201D; This pronouncement was issued to provide a consistent definition of fair value and ensure that the fair value measurement and disclosure requirements are similar between U.S. GAAP and IFRS. ASU 2011-04 changes certain fair value measurement principles and enhances the disclosure requirements particularly for level 3 fair value measurements. This pronouncement is effective for reporting periods beginning on or after December&nbsp;15, 2011. </font><font style="display: inline;">The adoption of ASU 2011-04 did not </font><font style="display: inline;">have a </font><font style="display: inline;">material</font><font style="display: inline;"> impact to our consolidated financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In June&nbsp;2011, the FASB issued ASU No.&nbsp;2011-05, &#x201C;Presentation of Comprehensive Income.&#x201D; ASU 2011-05 eliminates the option to report other comprehensive income and its components in the statement of changes in stockholders&#x2019; equity and requires an entity to present the total of comprehensive income, the components of net income and the components of other comprehensive income either in a single continuous statement or in two separate but consecutive statements. This pronouncement </font><font style="display: inline;">was</font><font style="display: inline;"> effective for fiscal years, and interim periods within those years, beginning after December&nbsp;15,&nbsp;2011. Due to the fact that ASU 2011-05 concerns presentation and disclosure only, </font><font style="display: inline;">our adoption of this standard in 2012</font><font style="display: inline;"> did not have a</font><font style="display: inline;"> material</font><font style="display: inline;"> impact on the consolidated financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In September 2011, the </font><font style="display: inline;">FASB</font><font style="display: inline;"> issued A</font><font style="display: inline;">SU</font><font style="display: inline;"> No. 2011-08, &#x201C;Testing Goodwill for Impairment.&#x201D; This pronouncement was issued to allow companies to assess qualitative factors to determine if it is more-likely-than-not that goodwill might be impaired and whether it is necessary to perform the two-step goodwill impairment test required under current accounting s</font><font style="display: inline;">tandards. This pronouncement wa</font><font style="display: inline;">s effective for reporting periods beginning after December 15, 2011. The adoption of ASU 2011-08 did not have a </font><font style="display: inline;">material</font><font style="display: inline;"> impact to our consolidated financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In December 2011, the F</font><font style="display: inline;">ASB issued ASU No. 2011-12, &#x201C;Deferral of the Effective Date for Amendments to the Presentation</font><font style="display: inline;"> of Reclassifications of Items o</font><font style="display: inline;">ut of Accumulated Other Comprehensive Income in Accounting Standards Update No. 2011-05.&#x201D; This pronouncement was issued due to Stakeholders raising concerns that the new presentation requirements about reclassifications of items out of accumulated other comprehensive income would be difficult for preparers and may add unnecessary complexity to financial statements and </font><font style="display: inline;">was issued with the intent for c</font><font style="display: inline;">ompanies to defer only those changes in ASU 2011-05 that relate to the presentation of reclassification adjustments until the Board is able to reconsider certain paragraphs. </font><font style="display: inline;">This pronouncement wa</font><font style="display: inline;">s effective for reporting periods beginning after December 15, 2011. The adoption of ASU 2011-</font><font style="display: inline;">12</font><font style="display: inline;"> did not have a </font><font style="display: inline;">material</font><font style="display: inline;"> impact to our consolidated financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In July 2012, the FASB issued ASU No. 2012-02, &#x201C;Testing Indefinite-Lived Intangible Assets for Impairment.&#x201D; This pronouncement was issued to simplify how an entity tests indefinite-lived intangible assets other than goodwill for impairment by providing entities with an option to perform a qualitative assessment to determine whether further impairment testing is necessary. This pronouncement is effective for reporting periods beginning after September 15, 2012. The adoption of ASU 2012-02 did not have a </font><font style="display: inline;">material</font><font style="display: inline;"> impact to our consolidated financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 840000 2034000 1743000 50400000 6345000 10055000 6500000 27500000 143116000 8742000 5159000 11400000 112500000 4178000 1137000
